==English==

===Etymology===
French ''[[morion#French|morion]]'', from Spanish ''[[morrión]]'', from ''[[morro]]'' ‘spherical object’, from Vulgar Latin ''*murrum'' ‘muzzle, snout’.  Compare ''[[moraine]]''.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/'mɒrɪən/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{cattag|armor}} A kind of open [[helmet]] used in the 16th and 17th centuries, having no [[visor]] or [[bever]], and somewhat resembling a [[hat]].
<!-- The definition above is verbatim from Websters 1913.  The quotation below was found by me.  Surprisingly similar, eh? :-) -->
#:*'''1786''': The '''morion''' is a kind of open helmet, without visor or bever, somewhat resembling a hat; it was commonly worn by the harqubussiers and musqueteers.  &mdash; Francis Grose, ''A Treatise on Ancient Armour and Weapons'', page 12.

